`Can't create/write to file'
----------------------------

If you get an error for some queries of the following type, it means
that MySQL can't create a temporary file for the result set in the
temporary directory:

     Can't create/write to file '\\sqla3fe_0.ism'.

The preceding error is a typical error message for Windows; the Unix
error message is similar.  The fix is to start `mysqld' with the
`--tmpdir' option or to add the option to the `[mysqld]' section of
your option file.  For example, to specify a directory of `C:\temp',
use these lines:

     [mysqld]
     tmpdir=C:/temp

The `C:\temp' directory must already exist. *Note Option files::.

Check also the error code that you get with `perror'. One reason the
server cannot write to a table is that the filesystem is full:

     shell> perror 28
     Error code  28:  No space left on device


